<p class="text-gray">Once upon a time I wanted to develop a translation intelligent-backed application for
  <span class="text-yellow">Namibian indigenous languages</span> particularly Oshiwambo, against English.
</p>

<p class="text-gray">One major obstacle was, and still is, lack of organised, open-source translation pairs.
  I know what you're thinking! Why not just source translations from an already available
  <span class="text-yellow" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" data-bs-placement="top" title="A dictionary or a word listing book.">
    embwiitya</span> like
  <a class="text-yellow text-decoration-none" target="_blank"
     href = "https://www.amazon.com/Oshindonga-English-Dictionary/dp/0868481823">this</a>
  or
  <a class="text-yellow text-decoration-none" target="_blank"
     href = "https://openlibrary.org/books/OL1268889M/Oshindonga_English_English_Oshindonga_embwiitya">this</a>?
  Not free!
</p>

<p class="text-gray">Hence why not create an online platform with trusted moderators where everyone can submit
  translations, and also learn?
</p>

